    "16560502492171dd33": {
      "type": "loop-article-richtext",
      "blocks": {
        "c17791aa-99c0-44b1-9c0e-b600e8c2dd36": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "#3: Asking better questions",
            "heading_size": "h2"
          }
        },
        "16560502493ef96db8-0": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>The way you frame a question can make a big difference to the quality of the response. Simply asking team members ‘What can I do better?’ is unlikely to generate much thought.<\/p><p>“Instead, try ‘What are the two main things that you think I could do differently?’”, Bas suggests. “In my experience, people will be quicker to come up with something that is real feedback. There’s less room to escape the question when you pinpoint it like that.”<\/p>"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "c17791aa-99c0-44b1-9c0e-b600e8c2dd36",
